# CollabText — project rules

This is a from-scratch CRDT-based collaborative text editor, built as a
portfolio project to demonstrate real systems/algorithms depth for SWE
internship recruiting. Every design decision must be defensible in a
technical interview — favor explicit, correct, well-tested code over
clever or terse code.

## Hard constraints

- NEVER use an existing CRDT library (Yjs, Automerge, ShareDB, etc.) for
  the core algorithm in packages/crdt. The entire point of this project
  is implementing the CRDT from scratch. You may use libraries for
  networking (ws), UI (React), and testing (vitest, fast-check).
- packages/crdt must have ZERO dependencies on networking or UI code.
  It should be importable and fully testable in complete isolation.
- Every function in packages/crdt must have a doc comment explaining
  WHY, not just what — e.g. why Lamport clocks instead of wall-clock
  timestamps, why tombstones instead of physical deletion.
- Do not implement a feature before its tests. When asked to build a
  phase, write the test file's structure and key test cases FIRST,
  confirm them with me, then implement.
- Do not silently expand scope. If you think a feature needs something
  not specified in the current prompt (e.g. authentication, multiple
  documents, rich text formatting), stop and ask rather than adding it.
- Prefer TypeScript strict mode. No `any` types without a comment
  explaining why it's unavoidable.
- Every package needs its own README-level header comment explaining
  its responsibility in one paragraph.

## Stack

- Monorepo via pnpm workspaces
- packages/crdt: TypeScript, zero runtime deps, vitest + fast-check for tests
- packages/server: Node.js, TypeScript, `ws` for WebSocket, vitest
- packages/client: React, TypeScript, vitest + React Testing Library

## Code style

- Explicit over clever. This code will be read line-by-line in
  interviews — prioritize a reader understanding WHY a line exists.
- Small, single-responsibility functions over large ones.
- Commit-sized changes: when asked to implement a phase, structure the
  work so it could be committed as 2-4 logical commits, not one dump.
